{"title_page": "John Hastings, 2nd Earl of Pembroke", "text_new": "{{Other people|John Hastings}}\n{{bots|deny=Citation bot}}\n{{short description|14th-century English nobleman}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n[[File:Sir John Hastings, 2nd Earl of Pembroke, KG.png|thumb|[[Coat of arms]] of Sir John Hastings, 2nd Earl of Pembroke, KG]]\n'''John Hastings, 2nd Earl of Pembroke''', [[Knight of the Garter|KG]] (1347\u20131375), was a fourteenth-century English [[Peerage of England|nobleman]] and soldier. He also held the title [[Baron Abergavenny]]. He was born in [[Sutton Valence]], the son of [[Laurence Hastings, 1st Earl of Pembroke]], and [[Agnes Mortimer, Countess of Pembroke|Agnes Mortimer]]. His father died when John Hastings was only a year old, and he became a ward of [[Edward III of England|King Edward III]] whilst remaining in his mother's care. The King arranged for John to marry Edward's daughter [[Margaret, Countess of Pembroke|Margaret]] in 1359, which drew John into the [[royal family]]. However, Margaret died two years later. John Hastings inherited his father's earldom, subsidiary titles and estates in 1368. The same year he made a second marriage, to Anne, daughter of [[Walter Manny, 1st Baron Manny|Walter, Lord Mauny]]. The following year Pembroke commenced the career in royal service that was to consume the rest of his life. The [[Hundred Years' War]] had recently reignited in France, and in 1369 Pembroke journeyed to [[Aquitaine]].\n\nThere he took part in a sequence of raids, sieges, and counter-measures against the French, with both notable successes and failures. The latter were compounded by his apparent inability to work alongside the famed soldier [[Sir John Chandos]], who, although head of the King's forces there, was far below Pembroke in rank. He was, however, far above Pembroke in ability, and his subsequent death led to even more problems for Pembroke in France. A couple of years later, the earl was summoned to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliament]] and returned to England. There, perhaps exasperated by the political failures of the king's ecclesiastical ministers, he was responsible for forcing them from power and being replaced by laymen. Pembroke was soon to return to France again, for what was to be the last time. In 1372 he set off with a small fleet, intending to raise a new army once in Aquitaine. However, his arrival had been anticipated by the [[Kingdom of Castile|Castilian]] navy (whose kingdom was then allied to France). Pembroke, outnumbered and outgunned, was forced to fight at the [[Battle of La Rochelle]], where he went down to a crushing defeat. Captured and taken to Castile, he was imprisoned in harsh conditions. It took a further three years for a large [[ransom]] to be negotiated, but in 1375, he was finally released. Returning to England through France, he was taken ill near Paris and died before reaching home. He was about 28 years old; his wife survived him, as did a son, born in 1372, whom Pembroke had never seen.{{Refn|The [[antiquarian]] [[William Dugdale]] relates the curse that had supposedly been on those that held the earldom of Pembroke ever since [[Aymer de Valence, 2nd Earl of Pembroke|Aymer de Valence, Earl of Pembroke]] had supported the execution of [[Thomas, 2nd Earl of Lancaster|Thomas, Earl of Lancaster]] in 1322. It was said, says Dugdale, that \"none of the succeeding Earls of ''Pembroke'' ever Saw his father, nor any Father of them took delight in seeing his Child.\"{{sfn|Dugdale|1675|p=18 n.7}}|group=note}} Also named  [[John Hastings, 3rd Earl of Pembroke|John]], he would eventually inherit the earldom. Pembroke was buried in [[Hereford]] in spring 1375.\n\n== Background and youth ==\n[[File:Sutton_Valence_Castle.jpg|left|thumb|Sutton Valence Castle]]\nJohn Hastings was born on 29 August 1347 at [[Sutton Valence Castle]], [[Kent]] and [[Baptism|baptised]] that day in the local church, St Mary the Virgin. He was the only son and [[heir]].{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} of [[Laurence Hastings, 1st Earl of Pembroke]] by his wife Agnes, who was [[Roger Mortimer, 1st Earl of March]]'s third daughter.{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} Laurence Hastings died exactly a year after his sons' birth,{{sfn|Jack|2004}} and John remained in the care of his mother,{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} whilst becoming a [[Ward (law)|ward]] of the King.{{sfn|Ormrod|2000|p=37}} In December that year his mother was [[grant (law)|grant]]ed 100 [[Mark (currency)|marks]] a year for his maintenance and upkeep.{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}}  His mother soon remarried, but her second husband (one John Haklyt) was himself dead by 1357.{{sfn|Jack|2004}} The [[wardship]] of Laurence's estates was divided between his wife Agnes, his mother (John's grandmother, Julian de Leybourne, who later married the [[William de Clinton, 1st Earl of Huntingdon|Earl of Huntingdon]]), and Sir John Grey of [[Ruthin]].{{sfn|Jack|2004}} John himself, in what was to be a gradual process, began receiving grants of [[manor]]s held by his father in 1362 and 1363. The following year, 1364, he received the wardship  of all his father's lands in England and Wales,{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} and was appointed [[Legal guardian|keeper]] of all his grandmother's [[dower]] lands. Hastings [[Proof of age|proved his age]] on 12 September 1368, made his [[Homage (feudal)|homage]] to the King and pledged his [[fealty]], and in return he was granted [[seisin]] of all his English inheritance. The following month, he entered into those estates his father had held in [[Ireland]] and Wales. Like his father, as well as being Earl of Pembroke, he also styled himself Lord of [[Wexford]] and [[Baron Bergavenny|Abergavenny]].{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} He soon became a [[favourite]] of the King.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=26}}\n\n=== Marriages ===\n\nPembroke married twice. The first was [[Arranged marriage|arranged]] by King Edward III, and took place on 19 May 1359 in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]] to [[Margaret, Countess of Pembroke|Margaret]] (1347\u20141361), [[Edward III of England|King Edward III]]'s twelve-year-old fourth daughter. She died around 1 October 1361,{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} probably of [[plague (disease)|plague]].{{sfn|Prestwich|1980|p=283}} and was buried in [[Abingdon Abbey]].{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} The marriage was never [[Solemnization|solemnized]]{{sfn|Ormrod|2013|p=414}} and they had no children.{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} This was an important match for the King;{{sfn|Waugh|1991|p=123}} the royal connection meant that, while his wife lived, Pembroke was referred to as the King's son in official records,{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} as his marriage had brought him directly into the royal family.{{sfn|Ormrod|2000|p=110}}\n\nHe then married, in July 1368, [[Anne Manny, 2nd Baroness Manny|Anne Mauny]] (24 July 1355{{snd}}3 April 1384). She was the daughter of the famed soldier [[Walter Manny, 1st Baron Manny|Walter, Lord Mauny]]{{sfn|Jack|2004}} and [[Margaret, Duchess of Norfolk|Margaret]], daughter of [[Thomas of Brotherton, 1st Earl of Norfolk|Thomas, Earl of Norfolk]], and later Duchess of Norfolk in her own right. Anne gave birth to a son by Hastings, who was known as John of Reading.{{sfn|Hasted|1798|pp=390\u201394}} Since his second wife was actually related to his first (they were cousins), a [[Papal dispensation]] was sought for this marriage, and received from the [[Simon Langham|Archbishop of Canterbury]] on 1 July 1368. In return, the Pope requested that the earl donate 1,000 [[gold florin]]s to the repair of [[Basilica of Saint Paul Outside the Walls|Saint Paul's]], [[Rome]].{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|ppp=390\u201394}} When his father-in-law died, Pembroke sent two of his [[knight]]s to take possession of all of Mauny's estates in [[Hainaut (province)|Hainaut]] for himself.{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} Pembroke was twenty-one at his second marriage, whilst his bride was only thirteen; Pembroke left her in England while he carved out a career for himself in France on royal service.{{sfn|Jack|2004}}\n\n== Military career ==\n[[File:Bourdeilles,_ch\u00e2teau.JPG|thumb|Bourdeilles Castle; captured by Pembroke soon after his arrival in France.]]\nMuch, if not most, of John Hastings' life was devoted to royal service, and this begun in October 1364 when he was in attendance on King Edward III at [[Dover]].{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} Five years later he [[entail]]ed  and [[Feoffment|enfeoffed]] a chunk of [[Earl of Pembroke|his earldom]], with the [[Reversion (law)|reversion]] going to the King;{{sfn|Ormrod|2000|p=109}} these were granted to his feoffees who granted them back to him for five years.{{sfn|Holmes|1957|p=54}} His first [[active service]] came in the same year, when he accompanied the King's son, the [[Edmund of Langley, 1st Duke of York|Earl of Cambridge]] to [[Aquitaine]],{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|ppp=390\u201394}} with a force of 400 [[men-at-arms]], to reinforce the Black Prince's campaign which had suffered severe setbacks following his intervention in the [[Crown of Castile#Ascension of the Trast\u00e1mara dynasty|war of Castilian succession]].{{sfn|Jack|2004}} They landed at [[St Malo]]{{sfn|Jack|2004}}\u2014apparently escaping the notice of a local French commander{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=27}}\u2014and began the long march south, aiming to join with Prince Edward in [[Angoul\u00eame]], whom they reached in late April 1369. They arrived at a period of military setbacks for the English, and [[Archambaud V of P\u00e9rigord|Archambaud]], [[Count of P\u00e9rigord]], was attempting to join forces with the [[Louis I, Duke of Anjou|Duke of Anjou]]; the earls of Pembroke and Cambridge were tasked immediately to destroy as much of Archambaud's lands as possible. This they excelled at, burning property and putting inhabitants to the sword.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=27}} After this [[chevauch\u00e9e]] into [[P\u00e9rigord]], Pembroke's force successfully captured [[Ch\u00e2teau de Bourdeilles|Bourdeilles castle]] after an eleven-week siege{{sfn|Jack|2004}}\u2013 mainly, in fact, due to the fact that the garrison made a mistimed [[sortie]] and allowed the English army entry.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=27}} [[Knighting|Knighted]] soon after by the Earl of Cambridge himself, {{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=27}} he continued to campaign in both [[Anjou]] and [[Poitou]],{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} involving much [[raid (military)|raid]]ing, some of it alongside [[Edward the Black Prince|Edward, Prince of Wales]].{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} By June Pembroke was raising a large army to relieve pressure on the north [[March (territory)|march]] of Poitou; he and Cambridge were joined by [[John Chandos|Sir John Chandos]] around this time. They arrived in the [[Vend\u00e9e]] at the end of June 1369,{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=29}} and captured [[Roche-sur-Yon]]{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} as a result of the French captain betraying the town to the English.{{sfn|Jack|2004}} This was one of the \"most significant enclaves\" the French held inside English France, and it belonged to \"no less a person\" that the Duke of Anjou himself.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=30}} Following the taking of Roche-sur-Yon Pembroke led a successful campaign into the [[Loire Valley]]. Although he failed on the first attempt to capture [[Saumur]], he took and held both of the main bridges across the [[River Loire]] between Saumur and [[Nantes]].  Already greatly fortified, Pembroke strengthened and garrisoned them. This campaign greatly diminished the ability of the French to attack through the western march of Poitou.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|pp=31\u201332}}\n\nBy this time, tensions had started appearing among the English generals, particularly between Pembroke and Chandos. This was based on their vastly different social status; as [[Jonathan Sumption, Lord Sumption|Jonathan Sumption]] put it, Pembroke \"may have had the grander name but his inexperience showed.\"{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=47}} Although Chandos had by now been appointed [[Seneschal of Anjou]], Pembroke\u2014with what a biographer terms \"aristocratic arrogance\"\u2014refused to serve under Chandos,{{sfn|Jack|2004}} who was, [[Richard Barber]] reminds us, only a banneret.{{sfn|Barber|2004}} It is possible that Pembroke was acting under the advice of his council, but either way, their armies were kept separate from each other on account of this.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=745}} As a result, that October (or, says Sumption, December){{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=47}} he invaded Anjou with just his own force of 300 [[lancer]]s{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} on a [[Arson|fire-raising]] raid to [[Puirenon]]. Pembroke spent long enough there to attract attention; he was [[ambush]]ed by [[Louis de Sancerre]] or [[Jean IV de Bueil|Jean de Bueil]] (both commanded the French forces to the east of the Loire) and about 600 men: \"Pembroke's men were still struggling to form lines across the village street when the French horsemen charged into them.\" About 100 of Pembroke's men were killed or captured, and he left behind a quantity of supplies, horses and [[materiel]].{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=47}} Not only was he unable to fight the attacking force off, but, having escaped to a house at the edge of the village, Pembroke was forced to call upon Chandos for his assistance{{sfn|Jack|2004}} {{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=47}} \"In revenge,\" says [[George Edward Cokayne|Cokayne]] in his [[The Complete Peerage|''Complete Peerage'']], he attacked the town again, before being despatched to relieve [[Belleperche Abbey|Belleperche]],{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} in early 1370, where he raised the French siege.{{sfn|Jack|2004}} At the same, Pembroke's own agents had recruited 300 men in England to join his force, and they were soon due to sail.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=69}}\n\n{{Quote box\n| quote = The earl of Pembroke and some knights had no other remedy but to retire, as quickly as they could, into an unembattled house, which belonged to the Knights Templars, without a moat, and only enclosed with a stone wall. All who could get there in time shut themselves in: the greater part of the others were slain or made prisoners, and their arms and their horses taken. The earl of Pembroke lost all his plate.{{sfn|Froissart|1808|p=12}}\n| source = [[Jean Froissart]], in his ''Chronicle'', on the rout of the Earl of Pembroke in 1369.\n| align = left\n| width = 25em\n| bgcolor = A5EDFC\n}}\n\nPembroke's embarrassment, says [[historian]] R. I. Jack, \"did nothing to abate the ill feeling between the two leaders\" and \"was a serious blow to Edward III's attempts to stabilize Aquitaine.\"{{sfn|Jack|2004}} Not only had the escapade damaged the English cause in the region, but it led directly to Chandos' failure later in the year to recapture [[Abbey Church of Saint-Savin-sur-Gartempe|Abbey]] at [[Saint-Savin, Vienne]], where Chandos' met an untimely death.{{sfn|Jack|2004}} This was a major loss for the English, as neither of the remaining English captains in France, including Pembroke, had the personal skill or qualities that Chandos had had.{{sfn|Jack|2004}} The  A contemporary [[chronicle]]r, [[Thomas Walsingham]], reported the French King, [[Charles V of France|Charles V]], when he heard of Chandos' death, said that no-one was now \"left able to make peace between England and France.\"{{sfn|Walsingham|1864|p=312}}\n\nIn early 1370 Pembroke was nominated for the [[Order of the Garter]],{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} and his Order [[Robe]]s were ordered for him, according to government accounts, on 12 March.{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} This timing allowed him to attend the order's annual feast in April. He took the [[Garter stall plate|stall]] of the deceased [[Thomas de Beauchamp, 12th Earl of Warwick|Thomas, Earl of Warwick]].{{sfn|Jack|2004}} The same year he accompanied the Black Prince\u2014who was by now suffering from the illness that was to kill him\u2014in a major campaign against [[Limoges]].{{sfn|Jack|2004}} Before commencing the attack, Pembroke accompanied the Prince (by now so ill that he could not stand), being conveyed on a [[Litter (vehicle)|litter]] \u2013 to [[Cognac, France|Cognac]], where the Prince's younger brother, [[John of Gaunt|John of Gaunt, Duke of Lancaster]] was due to arrive in September 1370.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=81}} Notably, one of Gaunt's closest advisors was Walter, Baron Manny, Pembroke's father-in-law. Mauny had already been directing much of the English campaign from London, and was \"no doubt frustrated to find himself dictating strategy to Pembroke from Westminster;\"{{sfn|Cushway|2011|pp=191\u2013207}} and when Gaunt eventually arrived, Pembroke's father-in-law arrived with him.{{sfn|Sumption|2004}} Limoges was captured after a five-day siege in which the English successfully [[Tunnel warfare#Medieval warfare|mined]] the city's walls. Following its capture in October 1370, the town was sacked and many inhabitants were [[Massacre of Limoges|killed]].;{{sfn|Sumption|2012|pp=82\u20133}} Pembroke appears to have taken full part in these events, dishing out harsh treatment to the occupants.{{sfn|Jack|2004}} He may even have engaged the captains of the town's [[garrison]] in [[personal combat]].{{sfn|Seward|2003|p=112}}\n\n=== England, France, and defeat at La Rochelle ===\nFollowing this, in January 1371 the Prince returned to England, while Pembroke remained in France and continued to prosecute the war, now alongside Gaunt. Together they besieged Montpaon from January to February 1371, after which, Pembroke himself was recalled to London in order for him to attend the coming parliament to which he had been summoned on 8 January earlier that year.{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} By this time, Pembroke dominated the [[Court (royal)|court]];{{sfn|Ormrod|2000|p=37}} although he was unable to persuade the King to assist him in Pembroke's dispute with [[Reginald Grey, 2nd Baron Grey de Ruthyn|Lord Grey of Ruthyn]].{{sfn|Ormrod|2000|p=112}}At this parliament,  which sat from February to March 1371,{{sfn|Jack|2004}} Pembroke was appointed a [[Trier of fact|trier of petitions]].{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} His business at this parliament was not purely administrative; Pembroke appears to have been the main leader of an [[Anti-clericalism|anti-clerical]] parliamentary faction which politically attacked the king's clerical ministers.{{sfn|Thomson|1983|p=143}} At least, so he was portrayed in some contemporary chronicles.{{sfn|Prestwich|1980|p=285}} His actions have been described as radical.{{sfn|McKisack|1991|p=291}} As a result of this assault, [[William of Wykeham]] and [[Thomas Brantingham]] (the [[Lord Chancellor|Chancellor]] and [[Lord High Treasurer|Treasurer]], respectively) were forced to resign, with their positions taken by [[laymen]].{{sfn|Thomson|1983|p=143}} Sumption suggests that the immediate cause for Pembroke's attack was his recent experiences at the [[front line]], in \"frustrating and underfunded campaigns\" whilst, at home, as the writer of a contemporary French [[tract (literature)|tract]] colourfully put it, \"the clergy reposed peacefully beneath shady canopies elegantly scoffing fat delicacies\"!{{sfn|Sumption|2012|pp=100\u20131}}\n\n==== Feud with Lord Grey of Ruthin ====\nWhile Pembroke was on campaign, Grey received word that the earl had died in France, and proceeded to enter Pembroke's [[Northamptonshire]] estate. This enraged Pembroke on his return to England in early 1371, and he petitioned the King at [[Marlborough Castle]] that September. Indeed, he probably complained to anyone who would listen; certainly [[William Latimer, 4th Baron Latimer|Lord Latimer]]'s [[Chamberlain (office)|Chamberlain]] <nowiki/>later testified that his master also discussed the event with Pembroke. Although, as Jack has since said, \"Latimer could find nothing{{Quote box\n| quote = Grey, on the strength of these rumours, entered the Hastings chace at Yardley Hastings in Northamptonshire and hunted there. When the foresters remonstrated, Reynold replied, 'Pourqouy me demandes et denyz de chacier i[c]y? par Dieu, si le Count de Penbrok vostre Seigneur, moerge sanz heir de son corps, ieo sera son heir et Seigneur de cest chace, et vous ne savez deinz compoye de temps, ieo serra vostre Seigneur.'{{sfn|Jack|1965|p=6}}\n| source = College of Arms, Proc. in Cur. Mar, vol. I, p.202.\n| align = left\n| width = 25em\n| salign = centre\n| bgcolor = A5EDFC\n}}\n\nmore comforting in reply than a reminder that Grey was, after all, Hastings next heir.\"{{Sfn|Jack|1965|p=|pp=5\u20136}}{{Refn|The detailed evidence for these events comes from legal depositions made in 1407, when Grey's case was first litigated. The surviving manuscripts are now held in the [[College of Arms]] (collated as MS ''Processus in Curia Marescalli'', 2 vols.){{sfn|Jack|1965|p=14 +n.1}}|group=note}}\n\nThis seems to have had little effect. Although Grey attempted to make peace with Pembroke (even coming to him on the very manor he himself had entered previously),{{Refn|And, it seems, in distinguished company: the earls of [[Humphrey de Bohun, 7th Earl of Hereford|Hereford]], [[Roger Mortimer, 4th Earl of March|March]] and [[William de Montagu, 2nd Earl of Salisbury|Salisbury]], were at Yardley Hastings with Pembroke.{{sfn|Jack|1965|pp=6\u20137}}|group=note}} Grey threatened him with disinheritance. \"The assembled magnates protested at this\": and Pembroke did not, at that time, carry out his threat.{{Sfn|Jack|1965|p=8}}\n\nPembroke was still in England in early 1372 (on which occasion his wife, now aged sixteen, became pregnant).{{sfn|Jack|2004}} Before he left\u2014still, as far as he knew, childless\u2014he arranged contingency plans in case he failed to return from campaign. To avoid Grey inheriting a penny in the event of Pembroke's death, the earl received the King's permission to make a further enfeoffment{{sfn|Given-Wilson|1997|pp=146\u201347}} following the one in 1369.{{sfn|Holmes|1957|p=54}} This specified that \u2013 after his debts had been paid{{sfn|Bean|1968|p=144}} \u2013 of much of his land in favour of a cousin, [[William de Beauchamp, 1st Baron Bergavenny|William Beauchamp]]. Beauchamp was not only his friend but in Pembroke's eyes a worthy successor to his title. [[Chris Given-Wilson]] has commented on this episode that \"few men acted in such an extreme fashion ... simply out of personal dislike.\"{{sfn|Given-Wilson|1997|pp=146\u201347}} However the situation never arose since he had a male heir born to him soon after.{{sfn|Bean|1968|p=144 n.4}}{{Refn|Yet the dispute had implications that echoed for the next sixty years or more, as up until 1436, the Lord Greys of Ruthin did indeed repeatedly claim to be [[heir-general]] of childless Earls of Pembroke. Although the Hastings line died out in 1389, the Greys' claim was then itself disputed by other families with dynastic links to the earls.{{sfn|Jack|1965|p=1}}|group=note}} Beauchamp was a younger son of [[Thomas de Beauchamp, 11th Earl of Warwick|Thomas, Earl of Warwick]], who had died of plague in 1369, and so was a cousin to Pembroke; they were on good terms, clearly.{{Refn|Pembroke and William Beauchamp were matrilineal cousins: Their mothers were both daughters of [[Roger Mortimer, 1st Earl of March]].{{sfn|Davies|2004}}{{sfn|Tuck|2004}}|group=note}} Thus began the process which did eventually result in Ruthin's disinheritance.  Much of the Hastings estates had been enfeoffed in 1369 and returned to him; now, in April 1372, he [[Quitclaim deed|quitclaimed]] them back to the feoffees again.{{Sfn|Jack|1965|p=8}} They were instructed that, if Pembroke died abroad, the Hastings estates were to go to the King and everything else to Beauchamp. Even if Beauchamp was not available, Ruthin was still out of the succession: the relatively-distantly related Sir William Clinton.{{Sfn|Jack|1965|p=8}}\n\n==== Return to France ====\nPembroke soon returned to France and the war. It is possible that he was personally requested to lead the campaign. He was, after all, the nearest thing to a member of the royal family, as well as the fact that to the Gascons at least, his previous efforts there had been looked on favourably.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=120}} By this time the government too viewed Pembroke as a \"military prodigy in the style of the 1330s.\"{{sfn|Cushway|2011|pp=191\u2013207}} On 5 March 1372 he [[indenture]]d with the King to serve in Aquitaine, to which end he was appointed [[Lieutenant of Aquitaine]].{{sfn|Hasted|1798|pp=80\u201398}} [[Mark Ormrod (historian)|Mark Ormrod]] has described the campaign as a minor one.{{sfn|Ormrod|2013|p=511}} This is because was accompanied only by his personal [[retinue]] of 160, in a fleet of \"little more than a dozen small vessels protected by three larger ships with towers.\"{{sfn|Jack|2004}} His appointment was on 20 April, and he sailed to the [[Bay of Biscay]] in June{{sfn|Jack|2004}} with a fleet of reinforcements.{{sfn|Prestwich|1980|p=184}} Not only did he carry with him extra troops but also, intending to raise a larger force once in Aquitaine, he took [[\u00a3]]12,000 in [[silver coin]] to pay for it.{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}}{{sfn|Jack|2004}} Pembroke was instructed to recruit 500 knights, 1,500 esquires, and 1,000 archers.{{sfn|Sherborne|1994|p=41}} He was sailing, however, with an overly-small fleet{{sfn|Cushway|2011|pp=191\u2013207}} (that was \"gravely inadequate\" commented [[James Sherborne]]){{sfn|Sherborne|1994|p=42}} and which was, tactically, being despatched prematurely.{{sfn|Cushway|2011|pp=191\u2013207}}\n\n===== Disinheritance of Lord Grey of Ruthin=====\nTraveling with Pembroke to France this time was William Beauchamp, and the later legal dockets indicate that whilst on campaign they continued to discuss Reginald Grey's disinheritance. We are told that, on one occasion when they shared a bed (\"''gisantz ensemble en un lit''\"),{{Refn|Not to be read in a modern sense of the phrase. As Constance Classen explained in 2012, \"Not even at night did individuals necessarily retreat to their own private space. Medieval beds were not only matrimonial, but familial... apprentices, students and soldiers would customarily sleep together and travellers might well be expected to share a bed at an inn.\"{{sfn|Classen|2012|p=3}}|group=note}} Pembroke told Sr William that Grey \"would not have as much of his inheritance as he thinks he will have\" and that he saw Grey as being \"joyful\" at Pembroke's death.{{Sfn|Jack|1965|p=8}}\n\n=== Defeat at La Rochelle ===\nThe plan appears to have been for Pembroke to land at [[La Rochelle]], giving succour to Poitou and [[Saintonge]],{{sfn|Harriss|2005|p=414}} and then, having strengthened Aquitaine, to have marched northwards, cross the Loire, and join up with King, in simultaneous campaigns.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=121}} Unknown to the English, however, Charles V's information from London was good enough that he knew of Pembroke' pending invasion of Aquitaine only a short time after Edward III's [[King's Council|Great Council]] had decided upon it.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=129}} [[File:Bataille navale devant La Rochelle XIVeme siecle.jpg|thumb|The Battle of La Rochelle as depicted in a [[Miniature art|miniature]] some time after 1380; note the English ships are deliberately illustrated as being lower than the Castilian.]]Pembroke though, was much delayed; although he was in [[Plymouth]] by May, his feet could not be available until June, due to a pressing shortage of ships.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=135}} Indeed, in light of the fact that the government was aware of the strength of the enemy's naval forces in the area Pembroke would be sailing to, says Sumption, the earl's own fleet was extremely vulnerable. Perhaps Pembroke expected only  to encounter [[Piracy|pirates]].{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=138}} But since it was known that both the French and Castilian fleets were at sea, this was still too small. Worse, since some of them had been hired from merchants, and others were individually so small that they could not be fortified.{{sfn|Cushway|2011|pp=191\u2013207}} Pembroke's ships reached La Rochelle on the afternoon of 22 June. Attempting to enter the harbour (the town was still held by the English), Pembroke encountered a much larger force of twelve large [[Kingdom of Castile|Castilian]] [[galley]]s,{{sfn|Jack|2004}} and eight [[carrack]]s.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=139}} They had been lying in wait for the English force ever since the latter's battle plans had become known weeks earlier,{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=193}} a French fleet under [[Owen of Wales]] was intended to join them, but arrived too late to take part.{{sfn|Amb\u00fchl|2013|p=662}} Battle was joined. Before hand, the earl knighted some of his own [[squire]]s on his [[flagship]].{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=193}} Pembroke was not averse to fighting; as a contemporary said, the earl and his army was \"marvellously pleased... for they did not think much of the Spanish and thought to beat them easily.\"{{sfn|Cushway|2011|pp=191\u2013207}}\n\n{{Quote box\n| quote = The knights of England and Poitou that day shewed excellent proofs of chivalry and prowess. The earl fought gallantly, seeking his enemies everywhere, and did extraordinary feats of arms... all the other knights behaved equally well.{{sfn|Froissart|1808|p=157}}\n| source = Froissart, ''Chronicle''.\n| align = left\n| width = 25em\n| border = \n| bgcolor = A5EDFC\n}}\n\nPembroke's smaller ships found themselves towered-over by the tall carracks, and Castilian [[Archery|archers]] rained arrows onto the decks of English ships, whilst well protected by their own  wooden [[Breastwork (fortification)|breastworks]]. Pembroke found his fleet caught between the enemy and the [[sandbanks]] (located off what later became [[La Pallice]]); further, the Castilian ships possessed [[arbalest]]s, which caused great destruction to wooden decks.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=193}} Pembroke was unable to replicate the victories of earlier years (for example, at [[Battle of Winchelsea|Winchelsea]] and [[Battle of N\u00e1jera|N\u00e1jera]]) due to his lack of archers, which would otherwise allowed him to lay down a [[Suppressive fire|suppressing fire]] on the enemy crews. Likewise, Castilian command of the air meant that English soldiers were unable to [[Naval boarding|board]] Castilian ships.{{sfn|Cushway|2011|pp=191\u2013207}} The battle lasted two days. The fighting broke off as night fell on the 22nd; Pembroke had lost two ships, and was now surrounded by the Castilian fleet over night. Fighting recommenced the next morning. Pembroke found his flagship attacked by four of the enemy galleys, who used [[grappling hook]]s to attach themselves to the English ship, and later managed to douse the decks of some ships with oil which could then be ignited by [[fire arrow]]s.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=140}} Fire, said, Sherborne, played a vital role in the Castilian triumph.{{sfn|Sherborne|1994|p=43}} Around this point\u2014with horses running wild and kicking holes in the [[hull (watercraft)|hull]]s{{sfn|Cushway|2011|pp=191\u2013207}} and his men throwing themselves overboard to avoid the flames\u2014Pembroke surrendered,{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=140}} much of his fleet burned or captured. Many of his retinue were killed, and those that survived were also captured. This number included Pembroke himself, as well as the [[Guichard d'Angle|Earl of Huntingdon]],{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}}{{sfn|Jack|2004}} and of course, the \u00a312,000 in silver, which was discovered untouched.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=140}} Historians have since been universally critical of Pembroke's actions at La Rochelle. The Victorian [[antiquarian]] J. H. Ramsay described Pembroke's defeat as worst ever inflicted on the English navy,{{sfn|Ramsay|1913|pp=22\u201323}} [[E. F. Jacob]], that it was a disastrous blow,{{sfn|Jacob|1947|pp=17\u201318}} and [[Anthony Steel (historian)|Anthony Steel]] said that it lost England control of the [[English Channel|Channel]] for several years.{{sfn|Steel|1962|p=19}}\n\n=== Capture, imprisonment and ransom ===\n[[File:090920_1148_6243_SLL_Curiel_Castillo_T91.jpg|left|thumb|[[Castle of Curiel de Duero|Curiel Castle]], 2009, where Pembroke was held for the early years of his imprisonment.]]\n\nFollowing his capture, Pembroke was taken to Castile,{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} along with about 160 of his men, 70 of them knights{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=140}} (\"with golden spurs\"){{sfn|Amb\u00fchl|2013|p=62 n}} and was paraded through [[Burgos]].{{sfn|Russell|1955|p=194}} There he was confined to prison, where he appears to have been treated poorly.{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} The Spanish, according to custom, transported prisoners \"bound with chains or cords, like dogs in leash,\"{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} or, as reportedly at [[Santander, Spain|Santander]], in [[Leg irons|irons]].{{sfn|Jack|2004}} Their treatment appalled even the Castilian's French allies: the French chronicler [[Jean Froissart]] wrote, of the Castilians, that \"they know no finer courtesy, just like the Germans.\"{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=141}}\n\nWhile in prison, he received the news as to his wife's pregnancy. A fellow prisoner, [[John Trailly|Sir John Trailly]], later reported to the 1407 inquiry of Pembroke's reaction. He was not, Trailly said, happy at the news as one might expect; rather, he was moved to anger, as now he had a son, if that son died without heirs, Pembroke's careful planning against Grey might be undone.{{Sfn|Jack|1965|p=9}}{{Refn|His fears, far from being unfounded, came true: Pembroke's son died early and without issue, and this enabled Grey's son to claim the inheritance as heir-general.{{sfn|Jack|1965|p=9}}|group=note}} A few months later, possibly after negotiation with the King of France,{{sfn|Amb\u00fchl|2013|p=63}} King [[Henry II of Castile]] agreed to sell his right to Pembroke's ransom to the [[Constable of France]], [[Bertrand du Guesclin]],{{sfn|Jack|2004}} for 120,000 [[French franc|francs]]. To do so, du Guesclin had to sell his Spanish lordship of [[Soria]]{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} and [[Molina de Arag\u00f3n|Molina]] (which he had previously captured from Spain),{{sfn|Jack|2004}} back to the King.{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} Pembroke's agreement with du Guesclin laid down that he would pay him 50,000 francs immediately, and the remainder within six weeks of Pembroke's arrival back in England. Pembroke's imprisonment was to continue for another three years, however, as\u2014despite Pembroke's supposed close connections at court and with the King{{sfn|Jack|2004}}\u2014there was little progress made in arranging for Pembroke's ransom, until early 1375.{{sfn|Jack|2004}} Meanwhile, Pembroke's own circumstances were especially harsh. He was lodged at [[Curiel de Duero|Curiel Castle]] in conditions bad enough to break his health.{{sfn|Sumption|2012|pp=141\u20132}}\n\nThe first instalment was eventually lodged in a short-term [[Moneylender|moneylending]] account{{sfn|Amb\u00fchl|2013|p=165}} for du Guesclin with a [[Flemish people|Fleming]] in [[Bruges]], by which time Pembroke was ill. He was taken by du Guesclin to Paris{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}}\u2014\"in short stages as kindly and gently as could be\"{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=142}}\u2014but the earl's increasing illness forced du Guesclin to make for [[Calais]] with all speed, as he had promised to facilitate the earl's return to England by [[Easter]].{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}}\n\n== Death and succession ==\n\nPembroke died in [[Picardy]] (at either [[Arras]] or [[Moreuil]]) on 16 April 1375, following his release from prison.{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} Despite a contemporary rumour that he had been [[Death by poisoning|poisoned]] by the Castilians, more likely causes were the dire conditions of (at least the early years) his imprisonment{{sfn|Jack|2004}} and sickness and fatigue brought on by his hard years of confinement. Cockayne notes that, because Pembroke died in France, and the balance of his ransom was to be paid to du Guesclin after the earl had returned to England, du Guesclin never received the balance of the ransom.{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}}{{Refn|Although the French King did grant him 50,000 francs towards compensation.{{sfn|Jack|1965|p=9 n.2}}|group=note}}\n\nPembroke was buried in the choir of the Friars Preachers, in [[Hereford]],{{sfn|Hasted|1798|pp=80\u201398}} some time after 28 April 1375; the King sent offerings for the earl's funeral. Pembroke had written two wills. The first was on 5 May 1372, which was superseded by another on 26 March 1374.{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} The first one declared that the earl  wanted all his debts paid \"by the hands of my executors and by the hands of the feoffees of my manors.\"{{sfn|Bean|1968|p=143}} The second will, [[Probate|proved]] in November 1376, made no mention of any feoffees, but did provide instructions for his funeral, particularly for his [[tomb]]. To this purpose he bequeathed \u00a3140, specifically requesting one to be built as grand as that of [[Elizabeth de Clare|Elizabeth de Burgh, Lady of Clare]].{{sfn|Ward|1992|p=162}} This was also to reward of his servants, and especially those who were with him in Castile and France.{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}}\n\nPembroke was succeeded by his son, [[John Hastings, 3rd Earl of Pembroke|John]], who had been born to Anne a few months after the earl's capture{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} and whom Pembroke was never to see.{{sfn|Jack|2004}}{{Refn|In fact, it was to be yet another in a number of occasions that no adult was available to inherit the earldom and the Hastings family endured a minority on that account.{{sfn|Keen|1996|p=170}}|name=|group=note}} Pembroke's wife had inherited her father's barony on his death in 1371, and outlived her husband until 1384. She continued to style herself Countess of Pembroke, as well as Lady of Abergavenny and Mauny, and received her dower in November 1375.{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|ppp=390\u201394}} The rest of the Hastings estates were held in w[[Ward (law)|ard]] by the King during the minority of Pembroke's young son.{{Sfn|Jack|1965|pp=9\u201310}}\n\n== Legacy ==\nContemporary rumour put his defeat at La Rochelle down to his being\u2014as  Cokayne put it\u2014\"a man of evil life, who had committed adultery, or to his having resolved to annul the liberties of the church.\"{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} Another contemporary [[The Anonimalle Chronicle|chronicler]] described him as a \"homme de graunt renoune.\"{{sfn|Cokayne|1945|pp=390\u201394}} Modern [[historiography]] has been rather more nuanced. Pembroke's recent biographer has noted a certain immaturity of character\u2014particularly in his relationship with John Chandos\u2014whilst also noting that the biggest defeat of his career does not necessarily indicate lack of leadership or judgement on his part. The truth, R. I. Jack says, is that \"Pembroke was luckless and arrogant, but not necessarily incompetent.\"{{sfn|Jack|2004}} [[Jonathan Sumption, Lord Sumption|Jonathan Sumption]] is more forgiving in is judgement, and describes Pembroke as an able man with, by the end of his life at least, \"political stature.\" {{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=142}} Sumption also sees Pembroke as \"intelligent, self-confident and ambitious,\"{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=26}} if also \"hot-headed.\"{{sfn|Sumption|2012|p=100}} [[Michael Prestwich]], meanwhile, has noted that Pembroke \"lacked the outstanding ability\" that Edward III's captains had possessed when the war began,{{sfn|Prestwich|1980|p=189}} and Mark Ormrod that he was a \"bellicose\" character{{sfn|Ormrod|2000|p=90}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=35Av5d0HKCQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Prisoners+of+War+in+the+Hundred+Years+War:+Ransom+Culture+in+the+Late+Middle+Ages&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjTuN_p2c3YAhVC6KQKHQNvAO0Q6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=Prisoners%20of%20War%20in%20the%20Hundred%20Years%20War%3A%20Ransom%20Culture%20in%20the%20Late%20Middle%20Ages|title=Prisoners of War in the Hundred Years War: Ransom Culture in the Late Middle Ages|last=Amb\u00fchl|first=R.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2013|isbn=1107010942|location=Cambridge|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/5110|title=Chandos, Sir John (d. 1370)|last=Barber|first=R.|date=2004|website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|publisher=Oxford University Press|access-date=20 February 2018|archive-date=20 February 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180220144316/http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-5110|url-status=live|url-access=subscription |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/The_Decline_of_English_Feudalism_1215_15.html?id=rHu7AAAAIAAJ|title=The Decline of English Feudalism|last=Bean|first=J. M. W.|publisher=Manchester University Press|year=1968|oclc=810527195|location=Manchester|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|author-last=Classen|author-first=C.|title=The Deepest Sense: A Cultural History of Touch|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c1RC8kSUfgEC&pg=PA4|date=2012|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Illinois|isbn=978-0-252-09440-8|p=3|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|title=The Complete Peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain and the United Kingdom: Extant, Extinct, or Dormant|last=Cokayne|first=G. E.|publisher=St Catherine Press|year=1945|isbn=|editor-last=Gibb|editor-first=V.|edition=14 volumes 1910 - 1959, 2nd|volume=X|location=London|pages=|oclc=1000621451|editor-last2=Doubleday|editor-first2=H. A.|editor-last3=White|editor-first3=G. H.|ed